# C# Access Modifiers (API only)

- This rule applies to `RentAll.Api` C# code. It does NOT apply to `RentAll.Ui` Angular/TypeScript.
- Always declare an explicit access modifier on every method, property, field, and constructor.
- Use `public`, `private`, `protected`, `internal`, or `protected internal` as appropriate.
- Always include `static` when the member is static.
- Do NOT rely on default visibility for methods, properties, or fields.
- `public` for interface implementations, controllers, DTOs exposed to callers, and manager methods required by `I*` contracts.
- `private` for internal helpers, builders, orchestration, and implementation details within a class or partial class.
- `private static` for static helpers that do not use instance state.

# Practical Example

```csharp
// ✅ GOOD
public async Task<JournalEntry> CreateJournalEntryFromReceiptAsync(Receipt receipt, Guid currentUser)
private async Task<JournalEntry> BuildJournalEntryFromReceiptAsync(Receipt receipt, List<ChartOfAccount> chartOfAccounts, AccountingOffice? accountingOffice, Guid currentUser)
private static bool IsCrossOfficeBankCardReceipt(Receipt receipt, BankCard bankCard)

// ❌ BAD
async Task<JournalEntry> BuildJournalEntryFromReceiptAsync(...)
static bool IsCrossOfficeBankCardReceipt(...)
```
